                  Metric spaces and fixed points

                  4.66

                  Let B(S) denote the set of all real-valued functions which are defined and bounded on a nonempty set S. If f∈B(S), let

                  ∥f∥=supx∈S|f(x)|

                  The number ∥f∥ is called the "sup norm" of f.

                  (a) Prove that the formula d(f,g)=∥f−g∥ defines a metric d on B(S).

                  (b) Prove that the metric space (B(s),d) is complete.

                  Proof

                  (a) By definition, d(f,g)≥0, since |f(x)−g(x)|=|g(x)−f(x)| for all x∈S, we can have supx∈S|f(x)−g(x)|=supx∈S|g(x)−f(x)| and d(f,g)=d(g,f). Use triangle inequality we have

                  |f(x)−g(x)|≤|f(x)−h(x)|+|h(x)−g(x)|≤∥f−h∥+∥h−g∥

                  which gives ∥f−g∥≤∥f−h∥+∥h−g∥, or d(f,h)≤d(f,g)+d(g,h).

                  (b) Let {fn} be a Cauchy sequence in (B(S),d), then ∀ε>0, there exist N>0 such that m,n>N means d(fn,fm)<ε, this means |fn(x)−fm(x)|<ε for all x∈S, thus for a fixed x∈S, the sequence {fn(x)} is a Cauchy sequence in R, thus converge to a point fx, define f(x)=fx,x∈S, then f∈B(S). Let m→∞ we have |fn(x)−fx|≤ε,∀x∈S whenever n>N, this means ∥fn−f∥≤ε, or d(fn,f)≤ε for n>N, so {fn} converges to f in (B(S),d).

                  4.67

                  Refer to Exercise 4.66 and let C(S) denote the subset of B(S) consisting of all functions continuous and bounded on S, where now S is a metric space.

                  (a) Prove that C(S) is a closed subset of B(S).

                  (b) Prove that the metric subspace C(S) is complete.

                  Proof

                  (a) Let f be an accumulation point of C(S), then ∀ε>0, there exist g∈C(S) such that d(f,g)=∥f−g∥<ε/3, Choose ε<1 we can see f is bounded on S, since |f(x)|<|g(x)|+1,x∈S and g is bounded. To see f is continuous on S, let a∈S, since g is continuous at a, we can find δ>0 such that

                  dS(x,a)<δ⟹|g(x)−g(a)|<ε/3

                  this means for x which satisfy dS(x,a)<δ, we have

                  |f(x)−f(a)|≤|f(x)−g(x)|+|g(x)−g(a)|+|g(a)−f(a)|<ε

                  thus f is continuous at a, and continuous on S, so f∈C(S) and C(S) is closed.

                  (b) Let {fn} be a Cauchy sequence in C(S)⊆B(S), then fn→f∈B(S) by Exercise 4.66(b), and use (a) we also get f∈C(S), so C(S) is complete.

                  4.68

                  Refer to the proof of the fixed-point theorem (Theorem 4.48) for notation.

                  (a) Prove that d(p,pn)≤d(x,f(x))αn/(1−α).

                  (b) Take f(x)=12(x+2/x),S=[1,+∞). Prove that f is a contraction of S with contraction constant α=12 and fixed point p=2. Form the sequence {pn} starting with x=p0=1 and show that |pn−2|≤2−n.

                  Proof

                  (a) From proof of Theorem 4.48 we have

                  d(pm,pn)≤cαn−αm1−α=d(x,f(x))αn−αm1−α

                  Let m→∞, then pm→p and αm→0, the conclusion follows.

                  (b) We have

                  x,y∈S⟹1xy∈(0,1]⟹|12−1xy|∈[0,1/2]

                  thus

                  d(f(x),f(y))=|12(x+2x)−12(y+2y)|=12|(x−y)+2xy(y−x)|=|x−y||12−1xy|≤12d(x,y)

                  This means f is a contraction of S, the contraction constant is α=1/2. To get the fixed point p, we know p=f(p), as f(x)≥1 for x∈S, we have p≥1, so

                  p=12(p+2p)⟹p2=1p⟹p2=2⟹p=2

                  For the sequence {pn} starting from x=1, we have d(x,f(x))=1/2, thus use (a) we have

                  |pn−2|=d(pn,p)≤12(12)n1−12=2−n

                  4.69

                  Show by counterexamples that the fixed-point theorem for contractions need not hold if either (a) the underlying metric space is not complete, or (b) the contraction constant α≥1.

                  Solution

                  (a) Let S=(0,1/4], and f(x)=x2,x∈S, then

                  |f(x)−f(y)|=|x2−y2|=(x+y)|x−y|≤12|x−y|

                  but S is not complete, so f has no fixed points in S.

                  (b) Let S=[0,+∞) and f(x)=x+1, then S is complete but |f(x)−f(y)|=|x−y|, so f has no fixed point in S.

                  4.70

                  Let f:S→S be a function from a complete metric space (S,d) into itself. Assume there is a real sequence {αn} which converges to 0 such that d(fn(x),fn(y))≤αnd(x,y) for all n≥1 and all x,y∈S, where fn is the nth iterate of f. Prove that f has a unique fixed point.

                  Proof

                  We can find a m∈N such that αn≤1/2 whenever n≥m, thus fm satisfies

                  d(fm(x),fm(y))≤αmd(x,y)≤12d(x,y),∀x,y∈S

                  so fm is a contraction on S, thus has a unique fixed point p∈S, and fm(p)=p. Then we have

                  fm(f(p))=fm+1(p)=f(fm(p))=f(p)

                  thus f(p) is a fixed point of fm, which means f(p)=p, thus p is a fixed point of f. If there is any q∈S satisfies f(q)=q, then by iteration we have

                  fm(q)=fm−1(f(q))=fm−1(q)=⋯=f(q)=q

                  thus q=p and the fixed point is unique.

                  4.71

                  Let f:S→S be a function from a metric space (S,d) into itself such that

                  d(f(x),f(y))<d(x,y)

                  whenever x≠y.

                  (a) Prove that f has at most one fixed point, and give an example of such an f with no fixed point.

                  (b) If S is compact, prove that f has exactly one fixed point.

                  (c) Give an example with S compact in which f is not a contraction.

                  Solution

                  (a) Assume f has fixed points p,q, then d(f(p),f(q))=d(p,q), but d(f(p),f(q))<d(p,q) whenever p≠q, thus we must have p=q, so f cannot have more than one fixed point. One example of such an f with no fixed point is

                  f(x)=x,x∈(1,+∞)

                  (b) Let g(x)=d(x,f(x)) for x∈S, then g≥0, and

                  |g(x)−g(y)|=|d(x,f(x))−d(y,f(y))|=|d(x,f(x))−d(y,f(x))+d(y,f(x))−d(y,f(y))|≤|d(x,f(x))−d(y,f(x))|+|d(y,f(x))−d(y,f(y))|≤d(x,y)+d(f(x),f(y))<2d(x,y)

                  so g is continuous on S, since S is compact, g attains its minimum on S. Let g(p)=minx∈Sg(S), we shall prove g(p)=0, assume not, then g(p)>0, thus p≠f(p), let q=f(p)∈S, then

                  g(q)=d(q,f(q))=d(f(p),f(q))<d(p,q)=d(p,f(p))=g(p)

                  a contradiction to g(p)=minx∈Sg(S), thus g(p)=0 and p=f(p), so p is a fixed point of f, the uniqueness follows from (a).

                  (c) Let f(x)=2x for x∈[1,2], we have [1,2] being compact, and for ∀x,y∈[1,2] with x≠y, we have

                  |f(x)−f(y)|=2|x−y|=2|x−y|x+y<|x−y|

                  But f is not a contraction, given any α<1, choose

                  x=(3−αα+1)2>1,y=1

                  we have

                  |f(x)−f(y)|=23−αα+1+1|x−y|=α+12|x−y|>α|x−y|

                  4.72

                  Assume that f satisfies the condition in Exercise 4.71. If x∈S, let p0=x, pn+1=f(pn) and cn=d(pn,pn+1) for n≥0.

                  (a) Prove that {cn} is a decreasing sequence, and let c=limcn.

                  (b) Assume there is a subsequence {pk(n)} which converges to a point q in S. Prove that

                  c=d(q,f(q))=d(f(q),f[f(q)]).

                  Deduce that q is a fixed point of f and that pn→q.

                  Proof

                  (a) If n≥1, we have

                  cn=d(pn,pn+1)=d(f(pn−1),f(pn))<d(pn−1,pn)=cn−1

                  So {cn} is a decreasing sequence, since obviously cn≥0 for all n, it converges to some c.

                  (b) The condition given shows f is uniformly continuous on S, thus

                  c=limn→∞cn=limn→∞ck(n)=limn→∞d(pk(n),f(pk(n)))=d(q,f(q))

                  we can also have

                  c=limn→∞ck(n)+1=limn→∞d(pk(n)+1,f(pk(n)+1))=limn→∞d(f(pk(n)),f[f(pk(n))])=d(f(q),f[f(q)])

                  If c>0, then q≠f(q), which means d(f(q),f[f(q)])<d(q,f(q)), but both should equal to c, a contradiction. Thus c=0 and q is a fixed point of f.

                  Notice that c=limn→∞d(pn,pn+1) and limn→∞pk(n)=q, for any ε>0, we can find an integer N such that d(pk(n),q)<ε whenever n≥N, if we set m>k(N), then

                  d(pm,q)=d(f(pm−1),f(q))<d(pm−1,q)<⋯<d(pk(n),q)<ε

                  this means pm→q as m→∞.
